SYMPTOM_TEXT: urinating blood. It progressed to clots; Hematuria; urinary tract infection; acute cystitis with hematuria; This is a spontaneous report from a contactable consumer (patient). A 51-year-old female patient received BNT162B2, via an unspecified route of administration, administered in Arm Left on 14Aug2021 11:30 (Batch/Lot number was not reported) as dose 1, single for COVID-19 immunization/Covid Prevention. Medical history included microhematuria from an unknown date and unknown if ongoing and developed a keloid from getting the small pox vaccine on an unknown date. There were no concomitant medications. On 15Aug2021, the patient experienced urinating blood. it progressed to clots, hematuria, urinary tract infection and acute cystitis with hematuria. The events were assessed as serious (medically significant). The events resulted in Emergency Room visit and Physician Office visit. There were no prior vaccinations (within 4 weeks). The clinical course was reported as follows: Patient went to the emergency room. She was told her she had a urinary tract infection and was put on an antibiotic. She was convinced it was caused by the vaccine. She will be seeing a urologist for testing. She asked if she should get she get the second dose. The urologist told her to wait until she was scoped to see if anything was going on in bladder. Patient's height as 5 feet 2 and 7/8th inches. She had the shot on Saturday 14Aug2021 at 1130 am. The following morning she woke up feeling like she had a urinary tract infection. She started urinating blood. It progressed to clots. She went to the urgent care. They saw that the level was significant. After 36 hours she went to the urgent care. She was told to contact the doctors office. The office told her to go to the emergency room. She went to the hospital. They did the same test as the urgent care and had the same conclusion. Since age 21 she has had microhematuria. She sees a urologist every 6 months for testing. At the urgent care and hospital she had a kidney and bladder ultrasound. At the hospital they said she had acute cystitis with hematuria. The impression from the Kidney Renal Ultrasound was no hydro nephrosis or shadowing renal stones. The bilateral ureter jets were visualized. The kidneys are normal in echo texture. No evidence of hydro nephrosis or shadowing calculus. She was unable to find any information about someone having gross hematuria and if they should get the second dose. Her doctor will see if there is an underlying cause. This is not a normal reaction and should not have happened. The patient is apprehensive about getting the second dose. She found reports of other people having it from a creditable website. She does not have any details to provide. The patient underwent lab tests and procedures which included Kidney and Bladder Ultrasound: both normal in Aug2021. Therapeutic measures were taken as a result of urinary tract infection. The outcome of the event 'hematuria' was recovered in Aug2021 and outcome of the other events was unknown.  No follow-up attempts are possible; information about lot/batch number cannot be obtained. No further information is expected.

kidney transplant recipients who developed COVID-19 more than 14 days after receipt of 2 doses of SARSCoV- 2 mRNA vaccine, administered at the recommended dosing interval; kidney transplant recipients who developed COVID-19 more than 14 days after receipt of 2 doses of SARSCoV- 2 mRNA vaccine, administered at the recommended dosing interval; This is a literature report. This author reported similar events in four patients. This is first of four reports  Recently, a study showed that only 54% of organ transplant recipients developed a positive antibody response after 2 doses of SARS-CoV-2 mRNA vaccine and, among kidney transplant recipients, only 48% had an antibody response 4. At our center the seropositivity rate in organ transplant recipients was 37.2% 5.This suggests that a significant proportion of transplant recipients remain at risk for COVID-19 despite completing the vaccination series. Our center encourages COVID-19 vaccination for all transplant recipients. We estimate an active follow-up of approximately 1,680 fully vaccinated kidney transplant recipients. We had 8 kidney transplant recipients who developed COVID-19 more than 14 days after receipt of 2 doses of SARSCoV- 2 mRNA vaccine, administered at the recommended dosing interval. All patients were symptomatic, most commonly with fatigue and cough. The median age was 65 years old (range 36-73), 50% had received a previous transplant, the median time from the most recent transplant to the first dose of mRNA vaccine was 31 months (range 3 - 248), and 3 out of 8 patients had received thymoglobulin for induction in the 6 months preceding vaccination. All patients were on calcineurin inhibitor (CNI)-based immunosuppression and 7 of the 8 were on mycophenolate mofetil. CNI level goals were not changed during illness, anti-metabolite doses were reduced or held based on symptoms and severity, at the discretion of the nephrologist. Symptom onset and SARS-CoV-2 testing occurred at a median of 56 days (range 18-77) and 59 days (range 20-77) after the second dose of the vaccine, respectively. Three patients received casirivimab/imdevimab as outpatient and did not require hospital admission. Three patients were hospitalized and had a length of stay of 3 to 5 days, without requiring ICU admission or mechanical ventilation. All were discharged to home without oxygen. None of the patients had anti-SARS-CoV-2 spike protein antibody checked after vaccination or disease and viruses were not sequenced. Data on the COVID-19 vaccine effectiveness is emerging, however, vaccine effectiveness in the immunocompromised population is lacking. It is encouraging that our breakthrough cases of COVID-19 after vaccination were mild and associated with good outcomes. However, we should continue to encourage our patients to be vaccinated and also encourage vaccination of household members and close contacts. Recent guidance allowing fully vaccinated individuals to resume prepandemic activities probably should not apply to transplant recipients. SYMPTOM_TEXT: 92-year-old male nursing home resident recently diagnosed with Covid 3 days ago rapid test antigen test is positive here in the ER history of dementia presents to the hospital because of a fall.  Negative trauma work-up.  Patient's oxygen saturation was 90% on room air when he got here.  ER put him on 2 L and is 98% now.  Patient is not a good historian because of his dementia. Troponin 0.04.  No lymphopenia.  White count is normal.  Chest x-ray is normal.  Hip x-ray is normal.  CT head, CT cervical spine is normal.  EKG reveals rate controlled A. fib.  Patient has a history of chronic A. fib. Patient was admitted to medical floor, due to presenting symptoms MRI brain was obtained.  MRI did show evidence of recent ischemic change to posterior left frontal or parietal lobe.  He was started on aspirin in conjunction with home atorvastatin and Xarelto.  PT and OT were consulted, patient did have difficulty participating in PT, his understanding is fine however his hearing is significantly impaired and I think it was more of a communication issue rather than an understanding of directions issue.  On my exam today I was able to write out my questions and his diagnostic findings, he was able to answer questions appropriately and verbalized understanding of findings he was able to follow commands without difficulty.  Neurology was consulted, await their recommendations.  Once cleared by neurology plan for discharge for further PT.    Per daughter, patient does not appear he has had any significant change in his understanding though he does have continued weakness.  This is likely attributed to both covid and his recent stroke, after long discussion she would like to pursue further PT and strengthening.

SYMPTOM_TEXT: ED to Hosp-Admission Discharged 8/31/2021 - 9/2/2021 (2 days) - DECEASED 09/02/2021 Presenting Problem/History of Present Illness/Reason for Admission Thrombocytopenia [D69.6] History of myelodysplastic syndrome [Z86.2] Pneumonia due to COVID-19 virus [U07.1, J12.82]   Hospital Course Patient is an 86 yo gentleman with past medical history of MDS, on IV chemotherapy with Vidaza.  Most recent chemo was given 8/9/2021 through 8/17/2021. He also has past medical history of GERD, HTN, BPH, asthma, thrombocytopenia, COPD, HLD, CAD, PVD, AAA, TIA, Mobitz type II AV block, LVH.  He presented to ED from infusion center on 08/31/2021.  He was there for a platelet transfusion.  He was found to have a temperature and shaking chills.  For approximately 3 days prior to admission he had been having increasing cough productive of yellow sputum.   Pt lives at nursing facility where he was possible exposed to COVID.  In the ED he was found positive for COVID 19 pneumonia.     Initially on admission pt had fever and no hypoxia.  He was not initially started on dexamethasone.  Overnight he developed fevers which steadily climbed during the day.   Blood work in the morning showed a normal ferritin, elevated crp/LDH/trop and procalcitonin, normal LFT's  Mid afternoon pt became tachypnic and per nursing pt was more confused.  He was oriented to person, place and time when I examined him.  His temp increased and did not respond to tylenol.  Antibiotics were initiated due to concerns of possible bacterial pneumonia.  Repeat lab work was ordered.     I was contacted again around 6 pm that pt's temp was 106.  The call provider was contacted to see the pt at bedside. She was already aware of the situation. ICU was called and made aware of the pt.  They indicated that pt's condition was dire and family was updated on the pt's current status.  PT's sister who is POA was contacted and pt was made DNR/DNI.     Pt continued to decline overnight. Pt's sister, who is also his POA was contacted that and updated that he was actively dying.  Due to COVID she declined to come into the hospital.  Patient expired at 0758 09/02/2021

Follow up with PCP within 1-2 weeks regarding Covid-19, UTI, and CHF DETAILS OF HOSPITAL STAY Hospital Course: Patient is a 80 y.o. male with PMHx of DM2, CHF, CKD and multiple co-morbidities who presented with 2 days of fatigue, weakness, fevers, and cough with slight mucus production.    In the ED, he had elevated RR, hypoxic requiring 2L NC. Covid testing was positive. He was slightly anemic with thrombocytopenia and absolute lymphopenia. His blood sugars were 219, UA was concerning for infection, BNP elevated, CXR consistent with CHF. He was given fluids and started on Rocephin. He was admitted for Severe Covid-19 infection with acute hypoxic respiratory failure, abnormal UA, and acute on chronic CHF exacerbation.   On the unit, he was started on decadron and remdesivir. He initially required 2L NC. We continued rocephin for his abnormal UA and followed cultures. We started him on Lasix 40mg for Acute on Chronic CHF exacerbation.    Patient respiratory status improved during hospital stay, weaned to room air. Urine cultures grew Group G B-hemolytic Streptococci and he continued treatment with rocephin. Toward the end of his hospital stay, he had a significantly elevated d-dimer, though he was asymptomatic. Subsequent bilateral doppler USV of UE and LE was negative for DVT. Patient was able to be discharged and placed on 3 days of decadron and 3 days of Omnicef. Length of Hospital Stay: 3  Condition on Discharge: Stable and improved.

Date of Admission  09/03/2021   Date of Discharge  09/06/2021   Reason for Hospitalization   Covid+ 10 days, increased shortness of breath  Hospital Course   Please see admission H&P for complete details.  Briefly, the patient is a 77-year-old gentleman with very few medical problems who presented acutely with a worsening 3 to 4-day history of diarrhea nausea and vomiting.  He was brought in by his son who was concerned had recently been diagnosed with COVID-19.  According to him and the son he had symptoms for several weeks but only began to get worse that 3 to 4 days prior to presentation.  He is unable to eat or drink prior to this.  He had been prescribed hydroxychloroquine by her primary care provider as well as prednisone.  He was noted to be hypoxemic while in the emergency room.  He was started on dexamethasone and admitted to our inpatient unit.  He was vaccinated  Discharge Diagnoses      1.  Hypoxemia secondary to COVID-19  As above the patient was noted to be hypoxemic secondary to COVID-19.  He had a CT scan to evaluate for pulmonary emboli which was negative.  However, it did show findings consistent with groundglass opacities as we typically see with COVID-19.  He did peak at a total of 6 L required on 2 days post admission.  Was able to wean down to 3 L with activity.  He will be discharged with home oxygen and likely will require this from 1 to 2 months.  He should follow-up with his primary care provider as needed to determine any ongoing need for this.  He should avoid any activity involving fire or flames.  He is experience welder and is actually very familiar with these precautions  2.  COVID-19 pneumonia  As above patient was admitted with COVID-19 pneumonia.  He did also have GI symptoms with this.  I do suspect that he he was more acute than the family had thought.  Interestingly he had also had these skin lesions on his chest back thighs and legs that could be the cause of much of his prior discomfort.  However, I cannot quantify this.  He did respond to dexamethasone.  We started him on on remdesivir but stopped after noting bradycardia which is a known side effect of this medication.  3.  Dehydration likely secondary to diarrhea and vomiting secondary to COVID-19  Upon admission patient had mild AKI with creatinine of 1.3.  This responded well to fluid administration.  4.  Cutaneous skin lesions  The patient has extensive patches and plaques of his chest lower legs and around his waistband area he is says he has had these lesions for several years.  They tend to get better with steroid cream.  He has never had a biopsy of these.  Photos of these lesions were shared with her dermatology team who is on-call.  My personal concern is for cutaneous lymphoma.
HISTORY: history of hiatal hernia and some ill described skin infection

Hospitalized 8.30.21;  COVID-19 positive 8.31.21; fully vaccinated  Admission Date: 8/30/2021 Discharge Date: 09/06/2021 DETAILS OF HOSPITAL STAY: PRESENTING PROBLEM: Pneumonia of both lungs due to Pseudomonas species, unspecified part of lung [J15.1] Pseudomonal pneumonia [J15.1] Bronchiectasis [J47.9]   HOSPITAL COURSE: Patient is a 74 y.o. who has a past medical history significant for long-standing severe bronchiectasis of unclear etiology, heart failure with reduced ejection (NICM) complicated by severe aortic stenosis (for which she is currently undergoing evaluation for TAVR), atrial flutter on chronic Eliquis, and chronic anemia. She was admitted 8/30 for presumed exacerbation of her chronic bronchiectasis, with recent sputum cx having grown multi-drug resistant Pseudomonas aeruginosa. Historically, she has hx of isolation of multiple morphotypes of Pseudomonas, as well as hx of Burkholderia and Citrobacter in the past. She was admitted on the recommendation of her primary pulmonologist. She had failed 2 rounds of ciprofloxacin this month and was still having increased sputum production, cough. She grew pseudomonas again 8/19 but was resistant to oral agents. She was started initially on meropenem but after beign seen by ID was transitioned to ceftazidime which she tolerated well. CT thorax showed new foci of patchy and nodular infiltrates. Film array incidentally returned positive with COVID-19. She did have ongoing hemoptysis but NOT massive and was controlled. SHe was seen by pulmonology and ID throughout her course. Hemoptysis improved and stabilized. She was back to her baseline 2L O2. ID recommended continuing ceftaz through 9/14. SHe had a midline placed on 9/6 and was discharged home in stable condition with home visiting nurses and infusion setup to start at 1700 today. Her eliquis was resumed and she was told to monitor for further hemoptysis. PCP was messaged to have their staff set up a follow up appointment, even if virtual.   ROS Patient feels good today. Ready to go home. Excited to get home. No new symptoms. Coughing improving slowly. No further significant hemoptysis. No fevers no chills. Breathing easier.    CONSULTS / RECOMMENDATION: pulm ID INPATIENT PROCEDURES: Midline placed 09/06/2021

SYMPTOM_TEXT: ED to Hosp-Admission Discharged   9/2/2021 - 9/6/2021 (4 days)  Hospital Hospital Course:  Patient is an 83 y.o. year old female with a past medical history of GERD, anxiety, depression, mixed hyperlipidemia and acquired hypothyroidism, who was admitted with severe acute on chronic hyponatremia.  A problem based hospital course has been listed below;   o Acute on chronic hyponatremia, severe and symptomatic: Her sodium was 111 on admission (sodium of 127 on 8/27/2021).  This is most likely due to severe dehydration related to poor oral intake due to severe malaise, nausea and vomiting.  Urine studies along with low serum uric acid levels are suggestive of SIADH.  She received hypertonic saline due to symptomatic hyponatremia.  Due to overcorrection of sodium, she was also placed on D5 infusion at 100 mL/h as per nephrology recommendations.  Her sodium appropriately improved after that and was 130 at discharge which is close to her baseline.  She was advised to restrict total fluid intake to less than 1800 mL/day and her Wellbutrin was discontinued.  She was clinically and hemodynamically stable at the time of discharge.  She was advised to follow-up with her PCP within 5 days with repeat blood work.     o COVID-19 infection: The patient presented with severe malaise, weakness, cough, abdominal pain, nausea and vomiting.  Chest x-ray revealed no evidence of discrete infiltrate and there was no persistent hypoxia.  She received dexamethasone 6 mg IV every 24 hour for 5 days during hospital stay.  She was discharged on dexamethasone 6 mg daily for 5 more days to complete a course of 10 days of dexamethasone.     o Hypophosphatemia: Her phosphorus was down to 1.1 on 9/4/21 which improved to 2.5 after multiple repletion with IV K-Phos.   o Mixed hyperlipidemia: She is not on statin due to intolerance.   o Acquired hypothyroidism: She is on levothyroxine 50 mcg daily.   o GERD: She is on Protonix 40 mg daily.   o Anxiety/depression: Her mood is relatively stable at this time.  Her Wellbutrin was discontinued due to hyponatremia/SIADH and if needed, she should be placed on alternative antidepression/antianxiety medication as outpatient.

Patient seemed slightly nervous prior to vaccination. Shortly after we checked on the patient while he was in the post-vaccination observation area, the patient abruptly experienced syncope 5-10 minutes after receiving J&J vaccine while he was seated in the waiting area. The patient slid and/or flopped sideways out of the chair before we could stop his fall, and his head struck the floor, resulting in a 1" laceration on his right forehead.  Bleeding controlled with direct pressure and gauze. Patient quickly regained consciousness while in position he fell to, later brought to supine, with knees and feet elevated, and was A&O and PERRLA with BP 90/60 with radial pulse and HR in mid 50s, pale and diaphoretic, minimal nausea, no breathing issues, and mild pain and discomfort. Patient felt warm, wrapped ice pack applied and seemed to help.  NKA. Patient stated he had history of type 2 diabetes, regularly took metformin and may not have taken it earlier that day (later said he had taken it after all), and that he had in the past been hospitalized for 4 days for DKA. Patient stated that he had a history of syncope after injections, blood draws, and medical procedures or settings and that in the past he and his healthcare providers had chosen to have him lay down while getting vaccines or possibly certain other treatments. Patient stated he has recently been experiencing extremely stressful events in his life and that he had recently felt more difficulty concentrating or thinking.  Patient condition began to improve, with improvement in skin signs and vivaciousness in his conversation with us. FD arrived, patient symptoms and vitals continued to improve, the patient was moved by FD to a seated position, and FD applied steri-strips. Patient stated he did not want to go to a medical facility, in part because of medical anxiety, stating he felt he would likely have syncope again just from going to an ER or urgent care. Patient seemed well enough that with all factors considered emergency transport to the hospital did not seem to medical personnel present like it would be the best option for him. Arranged for patient to be driven home and monitored by family. Patient felt very sad and stressed for a moment.  We cleaned up his wound area while leaving the steri-strips in place, and recommended urgent care and PCP follow-up, and talked with him about caring for the laceration. We advised him he may have a concussion injury from his head impacting the ground. We advised him to follow up with a medical provider, and to have 911 called if any concerning signs or symptoms developed. We talked with his family and friends about how they should help him rest while monitoring for any complications and ensuring his safety. The patient remarked he felt much better than he had expected as we walked him to waiting vehicle, patient departed from scene in care of family to be driven home and monitored by family.
CUR_ILL: * Type 2 diabetes * Recent extremely stressful life events
HISTORY: * Type 2 diabetes * Stressful living situation * History of syncope after injections, blood draws, and medical procedures or settings.
PRIOR_VAX: Patient states he has regularly had syncope following vaccinations and medical procedures for much or all of his life.

This is likely completely unrelated to the vaccine, but since I received the vaccine while pregnant, I do think it is important for the CDC to have this information to evaluate.  I am a G1 P1, was G1 P0 at time of vaccination.  Received my Pfizer vaccine #1 at 28 weeks and 1 day, then shot # 2 at 30 weeks and 6 days.  I had a healthy pregnancy, due date was 5/12/21.  On 5/15/21 (3 days overdue), I experienced lower back pain.  After speaking with the on call OB/GYN, we determined it did not sound like back labor; I was still feeling fetal movement, etc... so she did not recommend that I needed to come in to be evaluated.  On the morning of 5/16/21, I felt decreased fetal movement, could not elicit movement from stimuli.  I went in to L&D triage, everything looked good, however they decided to induce me.  I was induced with Pitocin, then had my water broken.  I did have an epidural.  My labor went fine with no concerns about the baby's safety.  I delivered our son at 5:59 am on 5/17/21.  Within an hour of his birth, he began to have shallow respirations with color change, which evolved into 20-30 seconds of apnea with significant desaturation to the 20s.  He was intubated by 9:15 that morning.  He remained in the NICU for 9 days.  During his stay, he had a comprehensive work up.  It turns out that he had a perinatal stroke with hemorrhagic transformation.  The area of hemorrhage was his left temporal lobe.  He had subclinical seizures that correlated with his apneic episodes. The seizure activity is controlled with Keppra. Since his hospitalization, we have followed with neuro, heme, cardiology and Early Intervention.
LAB_DATA: 5/17/21-5/25/21 - NICU work up which included U/S - head, MRI, MRV, MRA, labs, echo, LP
CUR_ILL: None - healthy pregnancy - 30 weeks and 6 days pregnant at time of 2nd pfizer vaccine Shot #1 - 2/18/21; Shot #2 - 3/9/21

SYMPTOM_TEXT: Mainly I noticed it at night, because it would wake me up 45 minutes I would try to go to sleep. It was like someone was tearing the muscles of my bone. I could not sleep. It was so bad. That would be form my thigh all the way to my ankle. If I got up and move around it lessen but would not go away. It was a huge discomfort. I went to my general practitioner, and he diagnosed it as restless leg and gave me a medication that I did not like because it did not take the pain away and would make me really high so he gave me another one. They did not do any tests they just assume it was restless leg. I went to my husband's doctor and he said it was restless leg as well. So, I went to a specialist and he prescribed me Neupro. I take that at night. It does not make the pain away it just makes it tolerable. That only lasted for about 6 weeks. Into the 4th week I noticed it was not working as well so I contacted my doctor and asked if he would increase it. That was on 08/30/2021. For whatever reason he was so slow getting back to me. He also prescribed gabapentin. I started taking the gabapentin because I could not get the Neupro. But it is not working. They are just trying to figure out what it is. I only had blood work done and everything was normal. I am going to a vein specialist on 09/14/2021. I do have a stabbing pain on my chin and so I am hoping this is just a vein issue.

SYMPTOM_TEXT: While at home watching TV, I began to have pains in my shoulders. The pain started to move towards the center of my chest. Pain then started in my left shoulder and moved down my arm to my elbow and then in my wrist. I tried to rub the pain in my chest but it was a deep, not in the upper muscle area.   Fearing signs of a heart attack, I went to NYU Langone Long Island hospital. They performed an EKG, chest x-ray and took blood samples. I stayed for 8 hours. All results came back negative for a heart attack. I followed-up with my primary care physician and he recommend to hold off on the second Covid shot and to see a cardiologist. I have a stress test and follow-up later this month. Since the first Covid shot, the area of the shot in my left arm has been sore on a regular basis.

I was in so much pain I was taking 1000 mg of Tylenol every 4 hours to help manage the pain.  On the third or 4th night I was in so much pain at 2am, I thought I needed to go to the ER.  I started listening to a guided meditation and that helped me get through the pain.  I was trying to mentally preparing myself for this pain to be my new normal.  It was very scary. I have developed chronic idiopathic urticaria (hives) and dermatographia.  I can't be entirely sure that this condition has stemmed from the vaccine.  I only know that I'd never had chronic hives before I got the vaccine, so I figure it was worth reporting.  I manage this through Zyrtec (antihistamine) on a daily basis - I can't function without it.
LAB_DATA: I met with an allergist (thinking that I was having an allergic reaction to something).  She ordered blood work to check my thyroid antibodies and to check some common allergens.  The allergens were negative. SYMPTOM_TEXT: Patient is a 51-year-old lady with a past medical history of hypertension, GERD, anxiety, obesity who presented  initially with thrombocytopenia.   92K in April/May 2021.  She had previously had normal platelet counts in February 2021.  She did not have any medication changes during the time but did note receiving the Covid?19 vaccination in January/February of this year.  She has not had any easy bleeding or bruising but had noticed increased petechiae.  Initially her platelet counts were watched until she trended down to 29K in July 2021.  At that time she was started on pulse dose dexamethasone 40 mg x 4 days.  She states that initially her petechiae went away however after about 3 days of being off the steroids she noticed the petechiae returning.  She subsequently had a CBC checked which was notable for a platelet count of 2K on 8/19/2021.  She was transfused 2 units of platelets  .  Given her severe thrombocytopenia she was admitted on 8/20/2021 to continue high-dose steroids as well as initiate IVIG and rituximab therapy. She initially had treatment response with a platelet count of 138K on 8/26/2021. She continued outpatient rituximab and has since completed 3 doses. She was started on a steroid taper and then started to have worsening petechiae on 9/3/2021. She had a CBC checked at that time which was noted for platelet count of 9K. Her steroids were increased at that time however she continued to have fatigue and petechiae and recheck CBC on 9/7/2021 was notable for platelet count of 1K. She was admitted and has started back on pulse dose Solu-Medrol and was given 2 units of platelets  9/8 with improvement of her platelet count of 26K.   She overall feels well and denies any unexplained fevers, chills, headaches, chest pain, palpitation, shortness of breath, cough, nausea, vomiting, diarrhea, weakness/fatigue. Has noticed some easy bruising as well as some mild vaginal bleeding over the past 24-48 hours.
OTHER_MEDS: alprazolam, cetirizine, escitalopram, hydrochlorothiazide, metoprolol, omeprazole
HISTORY: Benign essential hypertension generalized anxiety disorder Depression GERD
ALLERGIES: rabeprazole, aspirin, erythromycin, minocycline, tetracycline, colestid, hydrochlorothiazide/triamterene, Glucophage, amlodipine

The child was receiving a catch up vaccination schedule. RN reviewed the forecast and removed the vaccine from storage for administration. MA prepared and administered the dose. The error was caught immediately after administration. The parent was assured while the dose was early is should not harm the child but may not count as valid and that the next dose is due in 6 months. The parent left abruptly and went to the clinic where she was seen by Dr. who contacted this clinic and was informed of the nature of the error.  Upon research the DTaP dose is valid and the child will need another dose of Kinrix in 6 months to complete her series (dose #5 of DTaP and valid dose #4 of IPV). Physician notified by email of the dose being valid and messages left by phone for mom who is not returning calls.

Friend said they had been drinking and snorting cocaine. Upon arrival of first hospital, patient was tachycardic, confused, had LLE pain, and left buttock pain (concerning for compartment syndrome). CT angio runoff of bilateral LE showed nonspecific muscular edema involving left gluteus, adductor musculature, and left hamstring musculature. CXR results consistent with pneumonia. Initial procal was 12 at another hospital, was 47 when arrived here. Initial CK was 40,000, but had increased to more than 80,000 one day later. K+ was 8.9 and serum creatinine was 3. BNP was 314 and lactate was 3.3. Patient required pressors at first hospital (dobutamine and levophed) but was off by the time he arrived here. UDS was presumed positive for cocaine. Initial EF was 20-30%, which was concerning for cardiogenic shock. Once transferred to MICU, patient was treated for rhabdomyolysis and hyperkalemia. Treated hyperkalemia with bicarb, dextrose, insulin, and calcium. Rhabdo was treated with IV fluid resuscitation (lactated ringers). It is unclear if events was substance use rhabdomyolysis or vaccine induced. Unable to verify causation.

While this happened, I felt some pressure on the upper sides of my skull, and my heart felt like it was beating very fast.  It cleared up after about 5 seconds - the smattering of specks went away in the opposite of when they came on.  Afterwards I felt ok, did the basic stroke test, but went to the emergency room. Pt received the second COVID shot on 8/31/21. On 9/1/21 he developed a headache, body aches, chills, and a low grade fever. On 9/3/21 he developed dull sternal chest pain that radiated to the center of his back, neck tightness, and bilateral shoulder pain around noon. He was also pale and diaphoretic.  Mom called the PCP after these symptoms started. PCP directed mom to take pt to the ED. He was taken to Hospital Emergency Room on 9/3/21. Chest pain resoled on its own before pt arrived in the ED, according to the ED report. In the ED labs were drawn, EKG, and Chest Xray were completed.  Pt was admitted to cardiology in stable condition for an echocardiogram in observation as well as to trend his cardiac enzymes. Pt was monitored overnight via telemetry. Echocardiogram was completed on 9/4/21. Two repeat Troponin levels were drawn the morning of 9/4/21, 6 hrs apart from one another. Pt was discharged home due to a normal echocardiogram and asymptomatic status. Pt has a follow up appointment with Cardiology on 9/9/21. Cardiology will do another echo and draw another Troponin level. Cardiology recommended no athletic activity until cleared by Cardiologist.
LAB_DATA: EKG and CXR were normal on 9/3/21. CMP, D Dimer, Sedimentation Rate were normal. CBC on 9/3/21 was normal outside of monocyte level of 13.1. Troponin on 9/3/21 was elevated at 251 ng/L. CRP on 9/3/21 was also elevated at 13 mg/L.  Troponin on 9/4/21 at 0400 was elevated at 378. Troponin level 6 hrs later at 1000 was still 378.  Echocardiogram on 9/4/21 showed a normal cardiac structure with normal ventricular function. No signs of acute mycoarditis.
CUR_ILL: Pt received his first COVID vaccine on 08/10/2021. Developed body aches, weakness, headache, stomachache,  "burping", and chills on 8/11/2021.

On 5/28/21 patient received a dose of the J&J Covid-19 vaccine incorrectly. The patient had asked for the Moderna Covid-19 vaccine, signed a consent form for a Moderna Covid-29 vaccine, and received a card that stated she received a Moderna shot. However in her chart it was entered that she received a J&J Covid-19 vaccine with a J&J lot number of 202A21A. Thinking she had received Moderna, the patient came back on 6/30/21 and received an actual dose of the Moderna Covid-19 vaccine. She thought that this was her second shot. We realized on  7/9/21 while looking through our records that there was an error. We spoke to all staff involved to understand what happened. Once we were able to piece together what happened the patient was informed on  8/2/21. Our Medical Director, spoke with her and reported the following: Reviewed that J and J is a solitary dose and did not require a booster.    Advised that I would not anticipate any harm from receiving both especially as we are now 5-6 weeks past the administration, but since the vaccines are under EUA and this would be a rare circumstance, there is not data about such.  Patient received information well.  Stated that the J and J was a "doozy" and she had side effects for 3 days.  Stated she did not have any side effects after the Moderna vaccine.  Stated she has been feeling good - went out of state and quarantined for 2 weeks after given the high rate of CoVID there.  She actually stated " I feel even better having had 2 shots now with this variant."  She told me she would be ready for her third shot whenever booster are advised.  She is requesting appointments for her oldest 2 children to receive the vaccine.  I will send that information to the vaccine scheduler.  She also needed an appt for her oldest to have a sports physical - I made that appointment.  She expressed concerns about her younger children being in school and unvaccinated and I empathized with her on the subject.    She did not have any questions or questions at the end of the conversation

Patient came in at 1400hrs to get second Pfizer vaccination.  She had her 1st vaccine on 04/28/2021 without any complication. She reported history of Seizure and had follow-up with PCP yesterday, as outpatient.  She reported taking Keppra and confirmed taking her daily dosage today.  She reported having a snack approximately 45 minutes prior to this visit, including fluid.   Patient drove here on her own with no problems. Her 2nd dosage was administered at 1405hrs.  She was directed to sit across the main floor in direct view of the providers to facilitate monitoring.  A full bottle of water was also given to patient. A few minutes later, Client developed a seizure.  This was witness by pharmacists, R/N (volunteer nurse today) and myself. Patient fell on the floor from the sitting position.  Immediate assistance was provided to keep her from any sharp objects or walls.  Her head and body was stabilized to prevent further injuries.  Patient had a good pulse throughout her seizure that lasted for about 8 minutes. Her breathing was also monitored and she vomited scant amount of sputum on carpet floor.  Good chest rise was observed and her color was normal.  Her skin felt very warm and so her sweater was removed to assist with body temperature.  No cyanosis was observed during the event.   ED was already alerted and they arrived at vaccination center at approximately 1415hrs.  After a few minutes, patient regained consciousness and was taken by EMS personnel to ER.  She was stable at the time of her transfer to EMS.

The Pfizer Covid-19 vaccine was diluted incorrectly. 2.0 mL was used instead of 1.8 mL.  We were notified  by the nurse who administered in 8/16/21. We called Pfizer before calling the patients to see what they recommended. They said they did not recommend giving the dose and that the CDC says that the dose should not be reported.  Our Medical Director called the patient on 9/7/21 and reported the following:  Advised her of the vaccine error around the CoVID shot.  2mL of saline used for diultion vs. 1.8mL.  Explained what that meant in terms of "extra salt water" being given.  Advised it was not a matter for an unknown substance being given.  Patient expressed concern and being upset. "I don't understand how this happened." "You're injecting people with things, how could you do this."  I apologized for the mistake and assured her that we were taking actions to correct our process in the future.   She expressed frustration that she is only finding out about the error now.  I again apologized.    She stated that the error made her not want to get the second dose.  I strongly advised that she get the second dose.  I explained that I've known her for several years and her kids.  I  would want her and the kids to be as protected as possible.  I advised that she does NOT have to receive the second dose here and I could understand if she makes that decision, but I advised strongly that she consider getting it elsewhere.  I also advised that we spoke with Pfizer and based on their recommendations and the CDC, they would not recommend that she needs any extra dosing and to just complete the second dose as previously planned.  Patient again expressed being upset at the error and at the delay in notification.  I again apologized and offered to help her in any way I could or answer any further questions.  She denied any and the conversation ended.

SYMPTOM_TEXT: Patient was here for a third dose booster. They previously received 2 doses of Pfizer. This third dose they accidentally received a  dose of Moderna. This error was noticed the next day. Our Medical Director called them on 9/7/21 to make sure that they were aware of what happened and to let them know that per the CDC they should be fine and should not repeat the dose. She reported: When I asked how he was today he responded "terrible."  He explained that he's had significant back pain.  He stated that he was advised to have surgery but he's heard bad things about that & is hesitant to do that.  He has an appt tomorrow for a shot at a pain clinic.  A pack with pills they gave prior helped only a little bit.  He also intends to see a chiropracter.  I extended my concern for his pain & encouraged him to keep his appt tomorrow with the pain clinic.  I then advised him of the reason for my call He had previously received 2 pfizer vaccines.  When he came in for the booster, he was given Moderna. Patient became very upset & began yelling & using profanity. He advised that since he & his brother had the shot that they've not felt right with headaches & arm soreness. "You messed us up." Was repeated several times He expressed concerns that we could have killed them.  I apologized for the error and assured him that we were reviewing what happened in order to make a corrective action plan to prevent it from happening again. He advised it was already too late as it happened to him & his brother.  I advised that per CDC guidance, it is not ideal to receive Moderna after receiving Pfizer, but it is possible & does not have to be re-boostered with Pfizer. Harm would also not be expected. He advised that he will be in contact with other groups for their opinion including his lawyer.  I advised that headache & arm soreness is typical after the immunizations - both Pfizer & Moderna - & that after several shots, the reactions may be intensified since the immune system is already primed to fight the disease.  He reiterated the above phrase with profanity.  He then asked if I had another else to say because he had several phone calls to make. I offered to answer any questions he may have & again apologized that the mistake happened.  He stated he did not have further questions & we would hear from his lawyer ...........

SYMPTOM_TEXT: Patient has received 2 doses of Pfizer. Came to for a third booster and accidentally received a dose of Moderna instead. This mistake was realized the next day. Our Medical Director reached out to inform them of the mistake and that per the CDC they were probably find but that the CDC recommends not to repeat the dose. She reported:  Reached out to patient again  Was able to speak with him this time. He was already aware of the error from his brother calling him.  He advised me that he and his brother have side effects of arm soreness, headache and generally not feeling well.  He advised that they did not have any side effects after the pfizer vaccines.  He was upset stating "this should have never happened" and "this is just messed up." I agreed that it should not have happened and apologized for it.  I assured him that we were looking into the incident and trying to determine why it occured and take action from preventing it in the future. He advised me that he and his brother both showed the nurse their cards prior to getting the vaccine so he again could not understand how it happened.  I  thanked him for sharing that information as it is important for us to understand what occured while we investigate the problem.  I advised that the CDC does not recommend mixing the Moderna and Pfizer vaccines but that it was a possibilty previously when Pfizer was on shortage and that no significant ill side effect would be anticipated.  He advised that he and his brother were ill with side effects as above.  I explained that the side effects they are experiencing are those anticipated with both vaccines and are likely to be intensified after having already received 2 shots from the immune system being primed to fight the disease.  He stated that he is upset that they are having any symptoms at all as they did not with pfizer and then hung up.

SYMPTOM_TEXT: I tested positive for COVID-19 On 07/22/ mild heartburn I was taking TUMS for it and it subsided, and a little bit of dizziness, and coughing, I also had a bitter, acid taste in my mouth. About the 07/31/2021, all the COVID-19 symptoms subsided. My heartburn became manageable. On 08/11/2021- I had the Pfizer Dose 1-Within that hour of getting the vaccine. I had a strong taste in my mouth. I accepted that as maybe the heartburn coming back. I woke up the middle of the night, like I was choking.  About the 3rd day, I was heavy on Tums, Pepcid and Prilosec and I was drinking a lot of water and chewing a lot of gum. Chewing a lot of gum gave me comfort. The Acid reflux got so bad I was sleeping up on the bed, I loaded up on Pepcid and started taking Prilosec, after 14 days it didn't do anything for me. On 08/22/2021, I went to ER, because I was not getting any relief from the heartburn with everything I was taking. They checked me as if I was having something wrong with my heart. I had pressure in my chest. I am treating it like it was heartburn and my chest was tight. Treatment at the hospital: A GI cocktail and Mylanta and Pepcid, it's supposed to numbing effect so I wouldn't have the tightness in my chest. I felt a little relief because it numbed it. Once it wore out, I still had the tightness in my chest. The Pepcid, TUMS, and Prilosec caused my heart pressure to go high. I'm trying to stick to the TUMs and chew gum and drink plenty of water. This weekend will be a month that I have really, really bad heartburn. I am still having the heartburn 1st thing in the morning. I try to prop myself up at night and try not to sleep flat. At this point, when I started adding in the Mylanta and Pepcid, the heartburn has gotten better. I am 56 years old and I have never had heartburn before. I had mild heartburn after COVID-19 and it went away. It came 2 or 3 times worse with the Pfizer Dose 1  vaccine. I will be following up with my doctor and try to get a referral to a GI Doctor within the next week or so, because I am concerned about taking the Mylanta, TUMS and Pepcid and the whole mix for too long and it causes my blood pressure to rise.
LAB_DATA: EKG- looked good; 2 sets of blood work- to see if I had a heart attack- but results were normal  regular lab to check everything in general- the anemia came up.
OTHER_MEDS: Losartan-hctz; vitamin D; women's multivitamin multi-mineral pill; diclofenac; PEPCID
HISTORY: High blood pressure (manageable); anemic -not taking anything for it

SYMPTOM_TEXT: After receiving the first dose of the vaccine, my right shoulder began to hurt within 10 minutes.  Over the next 2 weeks my arm was severely sore.  I was unable to even brush lightly upon my skin on my right arm from my shoulder to my elbow.  My armpit was extremely soar and was swollen.  It still feels swollen today.  I have a swollen lymphnod in my right armpit on mammogram and ultrasound.  I have the feeling of stinging that radiates from my armpit to my right breast that goes around my braline to my midback on the right side.  The pain in my shoulder has continued; it awakens me at night from sleeping now.  I cannot lay on either side as it causes pain in my shoulder that radiates down my arm.  I called my pcp within 2 weeks of the shot and was told this is just a reaction to the shot.  I also reported this again at my yearly physical and was told it would go away.  I has not gone away.  I reported this to my gynocologist who ordered a mammogram as I am having breast pain.  This showed a swollen lympnode in my armpit and an ultrasound was also ordered.  To this day I continue to have pain in my armpit, shoulder joint, arm, and breast.  It comes and goes, it last for hours or can be intermittent stabbing and stinging.  It has changed the quality of my life.  I now have an appointment 9/20/21 with an orthopedic doctor to look for help in relieving the shoulder pain.  I am constantly worried that this is going to cause cancer in my breast.  I wish I never got this vaccine.  I pray I can find relief of these symptoms.  When I was given the first shot, the shot was given higher up on my arm near my shoulder, could this be part of the reason I am experiencing this pain?  I have tried to find answers on my own along with my doctors.
LAB_DATA: Mammogram 6/7/21, ultrasound 6/21, going to orthopedic this month 9/20/21.

On September 1st, Chief contacted Captain asking if it would be possible to administer a third Moderna dose to the patient. Captain told Chief yes as he had seen the patient's name on the SOS Booster list from the reverse call back system. Patient was administered his 3rd dose that day.  On September 7th, another crew was out giving vaccines and were going down the call in list (a separate list) and came across Patient's information. His care taker called multiple times and gave two different names on two different program lists. They proceeded to vaccinate the patient unknowingly that he had been vaccinated on September 1st. After investigating why a fourth dose was given,  we found that the patients information on a program we use to log in patient information did not show the third dose. It was discovered that on September 1st he was listed as a different name and under a different phone number. On September 7th, on the other list,  he was listed as another name with different phone number. Patient suffers from Alzheimer's and didn't mention anything about receiving the third dose a week prior. Patient's caretaker showed up on September 8th and saw another CDC Card on the table with the 3rd dose information from the 7th. She reached out to us today and brought it to our attention.   Doses administered as follows: First Dose ? 02/03/2021 Second Dose ? 03/23/2021 Third Dose ? 09/01/2021 Fourth Dose ? 09/07/2021  Captain went to patient's residence today and spoke with the caretaker and checked in on the patient. The patient was feeling ok and did not appear to be suffering from any adverse reactions at that time. He told the caretaker to keep an eye on him and if any adverse reactions became obvious, to call his doctor or EMTs and then notify administration. Captain states he will stay connected with the caretaker throughout the week to check in on the patient.
OTHER_MEDS: Namzaric, Magnesium Oxide, Citalopram HBR, Amlodipine Benazepril ,Atorvastatin,  B-1, Centrum Silver, Folic Acid, Risperidone Trazodone, Meloxicam, Loratadine

I had a cyst in my left armpit.  It became swollen, and the mycosis flared, manifesting as a red rash on my chest , waist and arms.  The cyst had existed for several years and had been checked ten years previously, found to be benign.  The infection was not severe, treated with a hot compress and left to drain.  The mycosis flares rarely now, but it does so when I have an illness (e.g. bronchitis) or something like the infected cyst.  I treated the rash with clobetasol and light box, and it has disappeared as of 9/7/21.  The cyst is reduced considerably. This might have been unrelated to the vaccine.

SYMPTOM_TEXT: Mom brought patient in for vaccines, mom said patient ate a good meal before this appointment. Medical assistant gave the vaccine ordered for patient, to the patient on August 27, 2021, at 5:30 p.m. Before giving the vaccine, I instructed medical assistant, to make sure patient wait in the exam room for fifteen minutes after receiving the vaccine. She did not instruct patient to wait for 15 minutes. Mom left with patient after vaccine was given, shortly after vaccine was given medical assistant told me patient is not feeling well, she told me he was in one of the exam rooms, I went in quickly to see patient he was lying on the exam table, mom said he is feeling dizzy, patient did not fall, no loss of consciousness.  Patient looks slightly weak, but he was alert but looks tired and talking, he told me he was feeling dizzy, his pulse rate was good and strong, but his skin felt clammy. His vitals revealed a blood pressure decreased to 61/41, blood sugar was ordered his oxygen saturation was 98% on room air. SYMPTOM_TEXT: Morning of June 16, 2021, I began feeling pain in right abdomen and had a low-grade fever. By that evening, the pain was excruciating (9/10) and had a fever of 101. That night I went to the emergency room. The doctor assumed appendicitis and ordered a CT scan. The results showed no abnormalities. He ordered a future ultrasound to look for a ruptured ovarian cyst. Ultrasound showed that my reproductive system was "unremarkable" and showed no signs of a ruptured ovarian cyst or any other explanation for the pain. Three days later (06/19/2021) I started my menstrual cycle on schedule. It lasted the normal 6 days and had no unordinary pains. On July 17, 2021, I had my next menstrual cycle on schedule but it was extremely light and only lasted 2 days. Pain was unordinary. Negative pregnancy test. On August 9, 2021 I started my next menstrual cycle but it was 5 days early and extremely heavy resulting in more than usual pain and lasted 10 days. I have no prior history of abnormal menstrual cycles or reproductive complications/concerns.

SYMPTOM_TEXT: RN noted the client's husband asking the client if she was okay. RN responded to the client. RN noted the client seated in her seat but leaning forward. The client stated that her "heart is racing." The client reported a history of hyperthyroidism and stated that sometimes she feels her heart racing in the middle of the night. EMT responded. O2 was 99%. The client denied any shortness of breath or itching. The client reported shaking. RN noted shaking of the client's right hand. The client reported feeling "dizzy." RN left the scene to obtain the anti-gravity chair. RN responded with the anti-gravity chair. RN observed the client attempt to stand and fell back into the chair. No injury was noted by RN. RN responded. EMT prepared to assist the client into the anti-gravity chair. The client stood up partially, became unsteady, and EMT supported her into the anti-gravity chair. The anti-gravity chair was reclined to low-fowler's position. RN noted the client's eyes rolling back in her head and her head rolling to the side. The client was not verbally responsive for a few seconds. The client's husband responded. The client's husband said the client's current state was abnormal for the client. The client was oriented to person, place, time, but not situation. RN noted the client's speech was interrupted with periods of non-verbal responsiveness. RN activated EMS at 4:28PM. RN Responded. The client reported chest pressure to RN. The client and her husband denied any history of anxiety. The client reported history of allergy to "something blue." The client's husband stated the client has an allergy to contrast dye. RN  inquired if the client's current symptoms felt similar to her previous reaction to contrast dye. The client said "no." The client was intermittently squeezing RN hand and telling RN about her day in incomplete sentences. The phrases included "cooked chicken and rice" and "for kids." RN noted the client arching her neck and back intermittently trying to adjust her position in the chair. The client reported chest pressure radiating into her abdomen. Denied feeling nauseas or the urge to defecate or urinate. RN noted tears in the client's eyes. Vitals obtained at 16:35PM were as follows: HR 104, O2 99%. The client reported tingling all over her face. The client requested to be sat up and reported "I can't breathe." RN noted the client's hand on her chest and the client gasping for breath. RN noted the client's cheek and ear were cold. The client stated she felt like she was sweating. RN  recommended administration of Epinephrine per CoSD Emergency Life Support Manual. RN educated the client that she was about administer Epinephrine. The client was not verbally responsive. RN administered Epinephrine Injection, USP Auto-Injector 0.3mg into the anterolateral aspect of the right thigh at 4:37PM. RN noted the client verbally responsive. Client stated her breathing was improving. Chula Vista Fire Department assumed care at 4:38PM. RN was unable to administer Benadryl 50mg prior to the Fire Department assuming care. Client transported to. The exact time the client left the facility was not noted. VAERS completed. VAERS confirmation number.

Patient presented to the ED around 10pm on 4/21, ~one week after her J&J COVID vaccine (exact date of initial vaccination not confirmed but was reportedly 1 week prior) with abdominal pain and headache. She was found to have thrombocytopenia (Plt 38) on presentation as well as renal and ovarian vein thrombosis. CT head showed a large right frontal intraparenchymal hemorrhage. She was taken for urgent craniotomy on 9/5 with EVD placement. Brain tissue was noted to have bleeding spots unresponsive to cautery and requiring local hemostatic agents. Repeat imaging showed worsening infarction. She had continued elevated intracranial pressures, so was taken back to the OR on the morning of 9/6 for bilateral EVD placement to help relieve pressure. Given her thrombocytopenia, thrombosis, significantly elevated D-dimer, low fibrinogen, and +HIT Ab test, she was diagnosed with vaccine-induced thrombocytopenia and thrombosis (VITT). She was started on IVIG 1g/kg daily  x 2 days,  bivalirudin with supportive transfusions to maintain goal plts >50K, fibrinogen > 150. Despite this, her neurologic status deteriorated due to elevated pressures, clotting off of her EVDs, and ultimately was declared brain dead in the afternoon on 9/7.  Family withdrew supportive care and patient passed at 3:57PM on 9/7/21.
LAB_DATA: WBC 11.77, Hgb 13.2, Plt 31 (nadir). INR 1.4, PT 16.7, PTT 34.  D-Dimer > 40.00. Fibrinogen 74. Haptoglobin 192. LDH 158. HIT panel with strong positive, HIT optical density 2.552 (this was after she had already received IVIG and some transfusions).

I blew my nose as I was walking through the kitchen and I heard something pop in my inner ear (left side). I called my wife to bring a chair to sit on. I thought it would go away but it didn't. I was sweating in the chest area and feeling a little nauseous. It was going on so long I called an ambulance and they took me to ER. At the Hospital ER they did a CT scan and said they couldn't find any event in my brain. I did not have a stroke. No treatment at the hospital - but the ambulance EMT's gave me something under my tongue which kind of cleared things up in a hurry. But because I was still sweating they took me to ER. They only gave me some medications (prescribed them) - Meclizine 25 mg - one tablet three times daily as needed for dizziness. I know it did something to my inner ear - but they were treating me for Vertigo but I think I it was just from blowing my nose too hard. They also prescribed Ondansetron ODT - 4 mg for nausea - I never took one of those.  I didn't have need of those. Meclizine that I was taking - I am not taking it any longer - I almost feel like I became addicted to it. I haven't really needed it for awhile.

Patient admitted on 8/29/2021: Patient is a 70-year-old gentleman, who tested positive for COVID on Monday. He was treated with __________, has been at home and has been improving.  He said his onset of symptoms were the middle of last week.  This afternoon, he was walking when his right lower extremity became painful and then numb.  He has no antecedent claudication.  He came to the emergency room.  A CTA was performed, which shows a thrombus in the popliteal artery.  Patient discharged 9/1/2021: This is a 70-year-old gentleman, who is COVID positive that presented with acuteonset of right lower extremity pain, followed by numbness.  He underwent CTA that showed acute popliteal artery thrombosis with limb-threatening ischemia.  His foot was cool, pale, and beginning to become mottled with loss of sensation and movement and he also had absent Doppler signals below his groin.  It was felt that he would require emergent thrombectomy.  He was taken to the operating room on August 28th and underwent the above-stated procedure.  A long portion of acute thrombus was removed from his popliteal artery and below and he was noted to have good back bleeding and positive Doppler signals at the end of the case.  Postoperatively, he has done well.  He has been placed on warfarin therapy and currently is therapeutic with an INR in the 2-3 range.  We will alternate 7.5 and 5 mg of Coumadin daily. He is ambulating without difficulty.  His pain is controlled and he is ready for discharge home.

In May of 2021 I suddenly developed a sore right shoulder and upper arm, this progressively got worse.  The issue appeared coincident with a common cold that I contracted while in out of town at my mother's funeral. My PCP referred me to Spine clinic, believing I may have a spinal issue, however an MRI of my thoracic spine was OK. As the pain progressed in my right shoulder/upper arm, I was losing range of motion and the pain was getting worse.  I was given Meloxicam 15mg to alleviate swelling, and referred to physical therapy.  My therapist noted that my range of motion limitations were not consistent with his experience with rotator cuff impingements, which is what I had been diagnosed with by Spine Clinic.  Subsequent visits at Spine clinic have resulted in an ultrasound of my right shoulder and an MRI. I then received a cortisone shot in my right shoulder about 4 weeks ago, and am for the moment pain free. I am still in PT. I have not yet talked to my PCP, I see her on September 30 for my annual physical. I contacted her today to tell her about my submission of this form. I submitted information regarding my rotator cuff impingement diagnosis in a vSafe report on Sunday 9/5 and was contacted by a CDC medical person on Tuesday 9/7 by phone, and asked to complete this online form.

Moderna COVID-19 Vaccine EUA: COVID-19 case resulting in Hospitalization / Death. Patient received Pfizer Vaccines on 5/1/2021 and 5/29/2021. Presented to ED on 8/11/2021 with complaints of worsening symptoms over the past 10-11 days including generalized fatigue, body aches, weakness, decreased appetite, nausea, vomiting, diarrhea, dyspnea, and cough. Intubated 8/19.  His course was complicated by L pneumothorax requiring Left chest tube placement X 2.  He was given Decadron 10 d through 8/21. Completed course of Remdesevir 5 days. Course complicated by MSSA pneumonia and concern for fungal pneumonia. Was being treated with Ancef and Micafungin. However he rapidly declined on 9/2. The patient was with significant.  hypotension and bradycardia, despite vasopressin and levophed gtts. Atropine x 1 given.  Patient with full cardiac arrest at 1255 and CPR was initiated. Epinephrine 1mg given.  1257 pulse check revealed a pulse that progressed into vtach at 1259, shock x 1 at 200J with PEA and subsequent sinus tachycardia. 1303 patient again went into vtach and another shock x 1 at 200J given and amiodarone bolus of 150mg administered. Return of sinus tachycardia.  ABG revealed acidosis and 3 amps of bicarb were administered. At that time the patient's family was called and the wife and daughter arrived at bedside. The family decided at that time to make the patient comfort care. He was taken off the ventilator and passed at 1350.
LAB_DATA: Positive COVID-19 on 8/11/2021 using the Roche LIAT SARS Assay platform using PCR or equivalent nucleic acid amplification technology.

SYMPTOM_TEXT: Pfizer BioNTech COVID-19 Vaccine EUA: COVID-19 case resulting in Hospitalization / Death. Patient received Pfizer Vaccines on 2/25/2021 and 3/17/2021. Presented to another organizations ED on 8/7/2021 with complaints of hematuria in Foley bag, and pain in lower part of abdomen. Patient was subsequently found to have COVID infection that was asymptomatic (on room air throughout admission) and discharged on 8/12/2021. Patient subsequently presented to ED on 8/26/2021 with generalized weakness and altered mental status. Patient's mentation briefly improved with supplemental oxygen. Chest X-ray Atelectasis/infiltrate especially left mid and lower lung zones, clinical correlation recommended for developing acute pneumonia/pneumonitis. CT Chest shows occlusive and non occlusive PE  LUL, small bilat eff, bilat lower lobe consolidation. In ER patient was noted to be in atrial fibrillation with RVR and was initiated on cardizem. On Thursday I went to my doctors office where an EKG, urine sample, and blood work were done on me, both came back within normal range but I was severely dehydrated. They couldn?t figure out what was wrong, but said if the pain got worse to go to the ER. I woke up on Friday and the pain was worse. I hadn?t eaten in several days and had lost 15 lbs in one week. I went to the ER where they did blood work, a urine sample, an EKG, gave me a IV drip for my dehydration, and X-ray on my chest, and a CAT scan.  The CAT scan relieved I had a blood clot in my lung. I was immediately told to stop taking birth control and I was put on blood thinners, nausea medicine, ulcer medicine (although I didn?t have issues with my through, they just didn?t know what else to do to help with my eating/drinking complications) and blood thinners. I was worried because my current birth control kept me from having my period, so as soon as I was told to stop and put on blood thinners I had my period. Normally I have period that last 7 days and are heavy, but due to the blood thinners my period was extremely heavy flow. Even more than usual.

It was reported that the back of her throat "looked like Hiroshima", being bright red and her tongue "tripled in size". She had a fever and was sweating for a few days. Her armpits and groin "were on fire". She developed cellulitis around the injection site (vaccination site cellulitis). She felt pain behind her eyes and her eyes became red. It was also reported that her lymph nodes were swollen and that she "looked like a Fighting Championship fighter". She reported that antihistamines (unspecified) were not working (drug ineffective). She sought medical attention and there were no lab diagnostics/studies performed. The patient did not receive the 2nd dose of the vaccine due to her reactions. The outcome of drug ineffective to antihistamines was unknown. The outcome of remaining events was recovered on an unknown date (reported as a few weeks afterwards). The reporter considered anaphylactic reaction, vaccination site swelling, vaccination site discomfort, vaccination site cellulitis to be related to varicella virus vaccine live (oka/merck)(VARIVAX). The causality was not provided for other events.   Upon internal review, anaphylactic reaction to the vaccine was determined to be medically significant.

Nausea- Intense (6 hours); Arm pain- Persistent (3 days); pain began at the injection site and eventually moving towards and stopping at the elbow; pain began at the injection site and eventually moving towards and stopping at the elbow; Movement of the arm was significantly reduced; This is a spontaneous report from a contactable consumer (patient). A 30-year-old patient of an unspecified gender received bnt162b2 (PFIZER-BIONTECH COVID-19 VACCINE), dose 1 at the age of 30-years-old intramuscular, administered in Arm Left on 11Aug2021 11:35 (Batch/Lot Number: EW0196; Expiration Date: 30Sep2021) as DOSE 1, SINGLE for covid-19 immunisation.  Medical history was none.   There were no concomitant medications. On Wednesday, 11Aug2021 at approximately 11:35, the first dose of the COVID19 vaccine was received. Within 15 seconds pain began at the injection site (left arm, upper muscle) and eventually moving towards and stopping at the elbow. The pain observed and continued for three complete days was much like that of a tetanus shot arm pain, however a bit more intense. Movement of the arm was significantly reduced with no movement begin obtained until the morning of day 3 of the arm pain (persistent for 3 days). Additionally, on Wednesday, 11Aug2021 at approximately 19:30, intense nausea occurred. This nausea lasted for approximately six hours until the patient was able to fall asleep. Upon waking, the nausea had dissipated. Nausea and arm pain were considered to cause Persistent / Significant disability / Incapacity. No treatment was received for nausea and arm pain. The patient recovered from arm pain and nausea on an unspecified date in Aug2021; the outcome of Movement of the arm was significantly reduced was unknown while the patient did not recover from the other events.  Follow-up attempts are completed. No further information is expected.

The symptoms continued to get worse over the course of 5 minutes. At 10 minutes after the dose was given I retrieved the patient's spouse. At 10 minutes I administered 1 dose of 0.3mg epinephrine into the left outer thigh. I gave the other dose pen to the patient's spouse and sent them to the nearest emergency department. As they left I notified the ED that they would be arriving shortly.  Later about 1 hour later I called the patient to follow up at which point the patient informed me the ED personnel had taken chest x-rays and found a blood clot in her lungs. She was currently being treated for the blood clot and could breath easily. She explained to me that the doctors supposed she may have had an active COVID 19 infection recently and was asymptomatic until she came in today. It is my opinion that the vaccine did not cause the clot and that it happened to show up by chance.

On Thursday July 8th, five (5) days after my second shot I started to get really sick, which progressively got worse the next few days. Cough, runny nose, headache, rundown, tons of mucus, fevers, aches. Was coughing so hard it felt like I was coughing up my lungs. They started to feel depleted and out of air just sitting normal at rest. I could breathe just fine and even inhale large deep breaths with no problem but they just felt depleted. Kind of like if you exhaled all of your breath and push push push every bit of air out of your lungs then hold it, that feeling right there is how my lungs would feel at rest and normal breathing. A feeling of a little bit of pressure on the lungs. But also like they had some fluid in them that I had to try to cough out (very productive cough), and they kind of tickled causing the cough as well. Wife (nurse) listened to my lungs and lower left lobe sounded coarse. Missed work Friday July 9th. Felt horrible all weekend and got a rapid covid test on Saturday, July 10th. It came back negative. Continued to feel horrible all weekend. Missed work on Monday the 12th, and called the Doctor for an appointment. Had a virtual appointment and he prescribed me a z-pack for possible bronchitis. Missed work Tuesday July 13th, but was starting to feel a good bit better. Returned to work Wednesday July 14th. Symptoms continued to subside and eventually all disappeared except for the lung feeling and cough.  To this day, nearly two months later, my lungs still have not recovered. I still have the depleted feeling, feeling of pressure on them, feeling of something in them, slight tickle, all of which makes me cough several dozen times a day. I can breath just fine and take large deep breaths but just normal at rest my lungs feel horrible and wrong and depleted. Have gotten an X-Ray and CT both of which my doctor says are clear and now I?m on an inhaler Flovent HFA.  This all could be actual C19 related, a regular cold, or possibly vaccine related. A 62-year-old female patient received BNT162B2 (PFIZER-BIONTECH COVID-19 VACCINE, Solution for injection; Lot number: EN9581, Expiration date were not reported), intramuscularly, administered in the left arm on 30Jan2021 13:15 (at the age of 62-years-old), as dose 1, single for COVID-19 immunisation. Medical history included high blood pressure and palpitations. Concomitant medications included metoprolol succinate (TOPROL, 50 mg Tablet) taken for high blood pressure and palpitations, patient has been on it for 20 years; loratadine (CLARITIN) taken as premedication for vaccination from 30Jan2021; and levothyroxine sodium (SYNTHROID). Patient had no additional vaccines administered on same day of BNT162B2. Patient also has no history of previous immunization with Pfizer vaccine considered as suspect. On 30Jan2021, the patient experienced warm feeling in left arm at injection site and face (1-2 minutes after vaccine), increased heart rate (3-4 minutes after vaccine), salty taste in mouth (3-4 minutes after vaccine), and head felt out of touch (3-4 minutes after vaccine). It was reported that patient knew it was a personal choice of whether or not to get second dose, but she had a brief reaction from the first one. It felt like when you get IV contrast. In a matter of minutes, it was a warm feeling in her injection site arm and face and then her heart rate increased, but not dangerously high. She then had a salty taste in her mouth and her head felt out of touch for a few minutes. She can't really tell if it was related. It only lasted a few minutes and completely resolved. She was fine after that and went food shopping with no ill effects. She thought it was probably some additive in the vaccine because it happened so quickly. Some people said she had a Vaso-Vagal response and she said no. She is due for 2nd vaccine on Saturday. She wanted to know if anyone has any insight about any of the additives that may have caused this. Patient stated that the increased heart rate followed flushed face. She then stated it was not flushed but warm. She took a loratadine (CLARITIN) that morning because she heard horror stories and she did not know what vaccine she was getting. She wondered if her reaction would have been worse if she did not have that. She then said, if she wasn't on a beta blocker, maybe the heart rate would have been higher and maybe that prevented her from having a worse reaction. The events were reported as non-serious.  The patient underwent lab tests and procedures which included heart rate: increased on 30Jan2021. Events did not result to emergency room and physician office visit. The outcome of events was recovered on 30Jan2021.  No follow-up attempts are possible. No further information is expected.

SYMPTOM_TEXT: I have been menopausal with no bleeding events in the past 2 years. On 8/22/2021 I started having vaginal bleeding and cramps which lasted for 7 days and became very heavy with clotting at times. I was seen in the emergency room and by an ob/gyn. I had diagnostic tests and a full exam which ruled out any underlying medical conditions that could explain the bleeding. I learned by doing my own research and speaking within my social and professional circle that other women have also experienced unusual and untimely menstrual bleeding post Covid vaccinations. Ruling out anything else, I am suspicious that there could be a connection between my vaccinations and my post menopausal bleeding event as well. I also noticed unusually tender and sensitive nipples as well in weeks prior to the beginning of my bleeding event. After 7 days the bleeding stopped and has not returned as of yet.

SYMPTOM_TEXT: 75 year old female received first dose of mRNA-1273 (Moderna) COVID vaccine on March 17, 2021.  One week after, patient experienced numbness/tingling in toes of both feet, which resolved after several days.  Also patient experienced a toothache for which she went to her dentist.  Dentist expected patient needed a root canal, but was surprised that x-rays showed no problem.  Patient received second dose of mRNA-1273 COVID vaccine approximately April 14, 2021 and experienced the usual chills and fatigue for 2 days.  On July 13, 2021 patient suffered an appendicitis.  In examining patient for the appendicitis, the patient was diagnosed with atrial fibrillation.   An appendectomy was performed and patient was admitted to hospital for 3 days observation of the A Fib. This the 6th woman of which she is aware who has had an appendectomy after their COVID vaccines. Patient is currently on blood thinner (Eliquis) for potential blood clot and medication for the A Fib.  She also had itchy welts on her legs, possibly an allergic reaction to the contrast dye used in diagnosing her appendicitis, or sequelae of the vaccine. Patient received no other vaccines between 4 weeks prior to the first dose and the present date.  Patient saw cardiologist July 30, 2021.  Patient now has recurring episodes of numbness/tingling in fingers and toes, with pain in her toes. Prior to the vaccine, patient was extremely fit and healthy, with no prior health problems other than osteoporosis.  She worked out 5 to 6 hours a day, 6 days a week, is very thin and has no prior history of A Fib or any heart problems.  Patient is irate her health has been compromised by the vaccine, regrets taking it and wants to warn others of the damage the COVID vaccine can do. I just got a breakthrough case of COVID on 9/4/21, about 8 months after my first vaccine. And I am experiencing exactly the same vertigo-like and dizzy symptoms that I experienced two weeks after receiving my first dose. I did not want to blame the vaccine for my symptoms 8 months ago. I remember I went to get my second shot and needed a wheel chair because I was so dizzy, experiencing vertigo.  But I never thought of blaming the vaccine until now that I have COVID and the same symptoms have returned. Besides vertigo/dizziness, I also have roving superficial pains that migrate from one part of my body to another, then randomly go away.  Exactly like I experienced after the vaccines were administered.
LAB_DATA: My doctor prescribed Meclizine but it made me very groggy. She prescribed physical therapy. We tried everything: Epley Maneuver, neck exercises, and still no relief.  I lost several days of work because I felt so terrible. As the weeks went by, I gradually adjusted and found small relief from time to time.  After 8 months I had pretty much overcome the dizzy symptoms (most of the time), when I came down with COVID and all the dizziness and random pains returned on day 4 of the disease. I finally put two and two together that it must have been the vaccine.

LAB_DATA: I am a Nurse Anesthetist that worked during the COVID crisis in hot spot.  As primary workers, all staff was encouraged to get vaccinated - and to see the death and dying - we did.   Had my first dose in December, 2020, second dose in January, 2021. A few months later, my vision was changing ( known floaters as previously mentioned).  My eye doctor, performed further tests and diagnosed me as having Fuchs corneal dystrophy.  This ia an autosomal dominant trait, but why did it show its colors aggressively.  There is no alleviating treatments, but will probably have endothelial keraptoplasty in the future. HOWEVER, never hearing of this disease after 40 years in the health field, I looked more into this disease.  The last sentence in one optic journal stated  "...paraphasing...  due to increase knowledge with human genome, 96 newly discovered microRNAs are now discovered and associated with malignancies.  Fuch's corneal dystrophies are associated with breast cancer!    This really peaked my interest. Immediately got script for mammogram in May - abnormal,  June-confirmed abnormality,  July - ultrasound  -site found , August -biospsy confirmed breast cancer,  September - MRI confirmed site.  Now for surgery, Radiation treatments, and hormone therapy.  But I am not alone, I have a friend, newly diagnosed with breast cancer, co-workers newly diagnosed with gall bladder cancer, and pancreatic cancers, a friend with thymus cancer, etc.      I think you will see more and more cancers evidenced.  It may have taken a few months = or even years to raise its ugly head.  I truly hope that this is not a travestry.

LAB_DATA: See also above. Patient had port-a-cath  placed on 7/12/2021 and has started on neoadjuvant chemo therapy with Dr. with Oncology. I am not questioning  that the vaccine caused this cancer but if it was an accelerant to  a very small tumor which may have been present. Note patient had a negative BIRADS 2 mammogram on 11/12/19.  We are a small rural facility serving a relatively closed population and such cases are very rare but I have noted several since the spring. Will be reporting others also.
CUR_ILL: Healthy . She did have a family history of breast cancer in her mother
